{"timestamp": "2025-12-07 06:41:00.256513", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope\n- Objective: detect anomalies, localize faulty devices, and identify root causes in the OSPF-based enterprise network delivering DNS/DHCP and web services (web0.local…web3.local and web99.local via Nginx LB).\n\nSummary of Network Health\n- Core/distribution routing: Healthy. OSPF adjacencies are Full/DR or Full/Backup on core and dist routers (router_core_1, router_dist_1_1, router_dist_2_1). No signs of routing instability.\n- IP reachability: End-to-end ICMP across representative hosts and to the server farm works with 0% loss. RTTs are low (typically 1–5 ms) with occasional first-packet spikes (ARP warmup) and no sustained latency issues.\n- Link/queueing: No drops or queue buildup observed on server_access_router interfaces checked. fq_codel shows 0 drops and 0 backlog.\n- DNS: Name lookups for service names are fast (namelookup ~2–25 ms in curl tests). DNS server reachable and responsive.\n- DHCP: User hosts are obtaining dynamic addresses; routes point to dist gateways as expected.\n\nObserved Abnormal Behavior\n1) Backend web servers directly accessible from user subnets (policy violation)\n- By design, backend web servers “should not be directly accessible from the hosts.” However, both example hosts successfully accessed http://web0.local, http://web1.local, http://web2.local, and http://web3.local with HTTP content returned.\n- This indicates missing/incorrect access control between access/aggregation and the server farm (likely on/near server_access_router).\n\n2) Web servers are not running Apache as specified\n- The design calls for “Apache web servers” (web0.local…web3.local). On all web servers, apache2 is inactive (dead).\n- netstat shows tcp 0.0.0.0:80 LISTEN by python3 across web_server_0/1/2/3. The served content is a “Mock Big Page” with intentional chunk delays.\n- This deviates from the intended service stack and explains atypical HTTP timing behavior.\n\n3) Inconsistent HTTP performance to load-balanced service (web99.local)\n- From host_1_1_1_1: web99.local TTFB ~0.20–0.24 s, total ~1.0–1.05 s (consistently good).\n- From host_2_1_1_1: web99.local alternates between fast (~0.24 s TTFB, ~1.04 s total) and slow (~1.24–1.30 s TTFB, ~2.05–2.10 s total).\n- Direct backend tests to web0/1/2/3 show similar bimodal behavior: many runs have TTFB ~1.14–1.30 s and totals ~2.0 s; some runs are markedly faster (TTFB ~0.20–0.30 s, total ~1.0 s).\n- This variability via the LB indicates that at least one backend is significantly slower and is included in the LB rotation/hashing, producing inconsistent client experience.\n\nCorroborating Measurements\n- host_1_1_1_1 ping to 10.200.0.x (dns, LB, web servers): 0% loss; first-ICMP spikes (10–50 ms) followed by ~1–5 ms—consistent with ARP/neighbor resolution, not a transport issue.\n- server_access_router tc stats:\n  - eth1 (to web_server_0): very low volume (52 KB / 788 pkts).\n  - eth3 (to web_server_2): high volume (610 MB / 403k pkts).\n  - This suggests uneven load distribution or a hot backend (web_server_2), which can exacerbate slow responses.\n- Load balancer:\n  - Nginx is active and listening on :80.\n  - Upstream configuration content was not visible via quick grep; behavior implies it forwards to multiple backends with differing response profiles.\n\nFault Localization\n- Policy enforcement point: server_access_router (or adjacent filtering point) is not blocking direct client access to backend web servers.\n- Application layer (web servers):\n  - All web servers are running a Python-based mock HTTP service instead of Apache.\n  - The served content intentionally introduces per-chunk delays, causing longer TTFB/total times.\n  - Load skew evident toward web_server_2 (eth3 high usage), linking to slower end-user experience when LB selects or hashes to that backend.\n- Load balancer (Nginx on load_balancer):\n  - LB is functional but is including at least one slow backend in rotation, leading to inconsistent client TTFB depending on backend selection.\n\nRoot Cause Assessment\n- Access policy violation: Lack of ACL/segmentation to block direct access to backend servers from user subnets, contrary to the stated design.\n- Service misconfiguration: Web servers do not run Apache as per design; instead, a Python “Mock Big Page” app with artificial chunk delays is deployed, inherently producing higher TTFB/total times.\n- Performance variability through the LB: Inclusion of slower backends and apparent load imbalance (especially toward web_server_2) produce inconsistent user experience when accessing web99.local.\n\nConclusion\n- The routed network, OSPF control plane, and basic IP/DNS/DHCP transport are healthy.\n- The primary issues are at the application/policy layers: direct backend exposure (policy breach), incorrect server software stack, and non-uniform backend performance causing variable TTFB behind the load balancer.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 55356, "output_tokens": 5030, "total_tokens": 60386, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 54912}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3840}}}
